Introduction¶

We will be exploring the No_show database to try and figure out how the different variables contribute to no shows.

Some of the questions we will be asking include;

  1. What gender honours their appointments more?
  2. How do different age groups contribute to shows and no shows?
  3. Do people who received an SMS have more shows than those who did not receive an SMS.
  4. What features seem to be contributing more to no shows?
  5. Does the hospitals location plays any role in the number of now shows?

Data Cleaning¶

From our initial exploration of the data, we found out that we need to clean out a couple of items and we will be doing precisely that in this section. We will rename the columns and change the datatype of the scheduled and appointment dates to datetime. We will also drop the row that had the age value of -1.

In [22]:

#Let us convert the columns to lower case and replace hyphens with underscores
#app_df.columns = app_df.columns.str.lower().str.replace('-',"_") - one way to do this.
app_df.rename(lambda x: x.lower().replace("-","_"), axis=1, inplace=True)

#rename the appointmentday, schedule day and hipertension columns
app_df.rename(columns={'appointmentday':'app_day', 'scheduledday':'sch_day', 'hipertension':'hypertension','patientid':'pat_id','appointmentid':'app_id', 'handcap':'handicap'}, inplace=True)

#Create a function to change types, default type is datetime
def to_type(cols,df, t='M'):
    for c in cols:
        df[c] = df[c].astype(t)
        return df
#change types of the sch_day and app_day
columns =['sch_day', 'app_day']

app_df = to_type(columns,app_df)

#check to see if the cleaning is complete
print(app_df.columns)
app_df.info()

total_m = app_df.query('gender == "M"').shape[0]
total_f = app_df.query('gender == "F"').shape[0]

#Men nos shows and proportion to total men appoitments
m_ns = app_df.query('gender == "M" and no_show == "Yes"')
m_ns_p = m_ns.shape[0]/total_m

#Women nos shows and proportion to total men appoitments
f_ns = app_df.query('gender == "F" and no_show == "Yes"')

print(f"Proportion of women no shows to total female appointments : {round(f_ns_p*100,2)}%")

We can see from the above that the proportion of no shows for both men and women to each categories total appointments is approximately 20%. This means that in as much as more women show up, it may be because more of them make appointment.

2. How do different age groups contribute to shows and no shows?¶

In [27]:
#create age groups
age_bins= [0,18,40,60,100,130]
labels=['minors', 'adults', 'seniors','old','centenerian']
app_df['age_group']= pd.cut(app_df['age'], bins=age_bins, labels=labels, right=False)

#check for the distribution of no shows for different age groups
ns_df = app_df.query('no_show == "Yes"')
s_df = app_df.query('no_show == "No"')
age_group_ns = ns_df.age_group.value_counts()
age_group_s = s_df.age_group.value_counts()

#plot the distribution of no shows and shows for each age group

plt.bar(x = labels, height=age_group_ns, alpha=0.8, label='no show')
plt.bar(x = labels,height=age_group_s, alpha=0.5, label='show')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Appointments')
plt.title('Distribution of no shows for different age groups')
plt.legend();

The young and middle age population seems to have a higher proportion of no shows compared to the older populations. Let us investigate the young and middle ages populations further.

In [28]:
ns_proportions = app_df.groupby('age_group')['no_show'].value_counts(normalize=True)

categories = ['minors', 'adults', 'seniors','old','centenerian']

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,5, figsize=(25,6))

for index, cat in enumerate(categories):
    #print(index, ns_proportions[cat])
    ax[index].pie(ns_proportions[cat], labels=['show', 'no show'],labeldistance = None, autopct='%.2f', textprops={'fontsize': 15})
    ax[index].set_title(cat, fontsize=18)

fig.legend(['show', 'no show'], loc=6, fontsize=16)
fig.suptitle('Proportions of show to no shows for different age groups', fontsize=20);

From the above we can see that the more minors, seniors and old peopled show up for their appointments as compared to adults and centenerians.

Conclusions¶

From the EDA conducted, we were able to see that more women make medical appointments as compared to men. However, the proportions of no shows for both genders is almost the same. We also noted that more minors, seniors and old people show up for their appointments as compared to adults and centenerians. We also see that sending an sms does not guarantee people will show up. On the other hand, people with a scholarship, hypertension and, or diabetes tend to show up more for their appointment in contrast to alcoholics and those with a handicap. We can also see that some hospital locations have more no shows than others.

Further analysis of the data needs to be done to esstablish deeper relationships within the variables. We have not yet established what variables are more likely to contribute to less no shows and further statistical methods have to be applied to establish this.
